{"workflow_number":126,"workflow_id":"gastro-rectal-bleeding","title":"Rectal bleeding","specialty":"Gastroenterology","diagnosis":"Rectal bleeding documentation","research_status":"partial_source_support","research_status_label":"Partial source support","uae_applicability":"No exact UAE rectal-bleeding guideline was identified. UK evidence requires UAE clinician review and local escalation, referral, investigation, and follow-up pathways.","uae_findings":[{"finding_type":"partial_applicability","evidence_basis":"Structured source status remains partial_exact_source_verified."}],"source_references":[{"source_resolves":true,"source_id":"bsg-acute-lower-gi-bleeding-2019","title":"Diagnosis and management of acute lower gastrointestinal bleeding: guidelines from the British Society of Gastroenterology","issuing_organisation":"British Society of Gastroenterology","official_url":"https://www.bsg.org.uk/getattachment/6d80aa64-9d11-4923-8789-a2e9b08502ef/gutjnl-2018-317807.pdf?lang=en-US","jurisdiction":"United Kingdom","sections":[{"section_id":"bsg-lgib-2019-scope-presentation","heading":"Scope of the guideline and background presentation description","locator":"PDF pages 2–3; lines 193–229","evidence_summary":"Defines acute adult hospital lower gastrointestinal bleeding as bright or dark red blood per rectum, clots per rectum, or blood mixed with stool, while warning that brisk bleeding should not automatically be ascribed to haemorrhoids."},{"section_id":"bsg-lgib-2019-initial-assessment","heading":"Management algorithm — initial assessment and Oakland variables","locator":"PDF page 4; lines 267–316","evidence_summary":"Supports routine observations, full history and examination including digital rectal examination, appropriate blood tests, heart rate, systolic blood pressure, haemoglobin, and previous lower-GI-bleeding admission context."},{"section_id":"bsg-lgib-2019-antithrombotic-context","heading":"Abstract and recommendations — anticoagulant and antiplatelet context","locator":"PDF pages 1–2; lines 58–60 and 110–145","evidence_summary":"Supports documenting whether anticoagulant or antiplatelet treatment is relevant to acute lower gastrointestinal bleeding; medicine interruption, reversal, and restart instructions are deliberately not mapped."},{"section_id":"bsg-lgib-2019-stability-followup","heading":"Recommendations 1–4 and risk assessment","locator":"PDF pages 1 and 4; lines 63–84 and 267–352","evidence_summary":"Supports clinician assessment of haemodynamic stability, major versus minor bleeding context, and qualified clinician-decided hospital or outpatient follow-up documentation without calculating a score or inserting disposition advice."}]},{"source_resolves":true,"source_id":"nice-suspected-cancer-ng12-2026","title":"Suspected cancer: recognition and referral","issuing_organisation":"National Institute for Health and Care Excellence","official_url":"https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng12/chapter/recommendations-organised-by-site-of-cancer","jurisdiction":"England, United Kingdom","sections":[{"section_id":"nice-ng12-colorectal-rectal-bleeding","heading":"Recommendations 1.3.1–1.3.5 — colorectal cancer features","locator":"recommendations 1.3.1–1.3.5","evidence_summary":"Supports clinician recognition of rectal bleeding, change in bowel habit, abdominal pain, weight loss, anaemia, and rectal-mass contexts with recommendation-specific age qualifiers; it does not assert cancer."}]}],"evidence_links":[{"evidence_item_id":"gastro-rectal-bleeding--bsg-lgib-2019-scope-presentation","source_id":"bsg-acute-lower-gi-bleeding-2019","source_section_id":"bsg-lgib-2019-scope-presentation","direct_relationship":"Supports mapped acute lower-GI-bleeding presentation terms and blood colour or relation-to-stool fields without attributing a cause.","paraphrased_evidence_summary":"Defines acute adult hospital lower gastrointestinal bleeding as bright or dark red blood per rectum, clots per rectum, or blood mixed with stool, while warning that brisk bleeding should not automatically be ascribed to haemorrhoids.","content_mapping_status":"reviewed_not_mapped_to_legacy_content","candidate_status":"review_only_not_approved","source_resolves":true},{"evidence_item_id":"gastro-rectal-bleeding--bsg-lgib-2019-initial-assessment","source_id":"bsg-acute-lower-gi-bleeding-2019","source_section_id":"bsg-lgib-2019-initial-assessment","direct_relationship":"Supports mapped clinician-recorded examination, DRE, observations, blood pressure, heart rate, haemoglobin or CBC, and previous-bleed assessment fields.","paraphrased_evidence_summary":"Supports routine observations, full history and examination including digital rectal examination, appropriate blood tests, heart rate, systolic blood pressure, haemoglobin, and previous lower-GI-bleeding admission context.","content_mapping_status":"reviewed_not_mapped_to_legacy_content","candidate_status":"review_only_not_approved","source_resolves":true},{"evidence_item_id":"gastro-rectal-bleeding--bsg-lgib-2019-antithrombotic-context","source_id":"bsg-acute-lower-gi-bleeding-2019","source_section_id":"bsg-lgib-2019-antithrombotic-context","direct_relationship":"Supports documenting anticoagulant relevance only; no medicine change or reversal instruction is mapped.","paraphrased_evidence_summary":"Supports documenting whether anticoagulant or antiplatelet treatment is relevant to acute lower gastrointestinal bleeding; medicine interruption, reversal, and restart instructions are deliberately not mapped.","content_mapping_status":"reviewed_not_mapped_to_legacy_content","candidate_status":"review_only_not_approved","source_resolves":true},{"evidence_item_id":"gastro-rectal-bleeding--bsg-lgib-2019-stability-followup","source_id":"bsg-acute-lower-gi-bleeding-2019","source_section_id":"bsg-lgib-2019-stability-followup","direct_relationship":"Supports mapped haemodynamic-stability prompts and clinician-decided follow-up or referral documentation in qualified acute contexts; no score or disposition is generated.","paraphrased_evidence_summary":"Supports clinician assessment of haemodynamic stability, major versus minor bleeding context, and qualified clinician-decided hospital or outpatient follow-up documentation without calculating a score or inserting disposition advice.","content_mapping_status":"reviewed_not_mapped_to_legacy_content","candidate_status":"review_only_not_approved","source_resolves":true},{"evidence_item_id":"gastro-rectal-bleeding--nice-ng12-colorectal-rectal-bleeding","source_id":"nice-suspected-cancer-ng12-2026","source_section_id":"nice-ng12-colorectal-rectal-bleeding","direct_relationship":"Supports mapped rectal-bleeding combinations with age, weight-loss, and bowel-habit qualifiers as prompts only; no cancer diagnosis is asserted.","paraphrased_evidence_summary":"Supports clinician recognition of rectal bleeding, change in bowel habit, abdominal pain, weight loss, anaemia, and rectal-mass contexts with recommendation-specific age qualifiers; it does not assert cancer.","content_mapping_status":"reviewed_not_mapped_to_legacy_content","candidate_status":"review_only_not_approved","source_resolves":true}],"unsupported_item_count":72,"safety_review_required_count":72,"unresolved_source_gaps":["The BSG source excludes uncomplicated primary-care LGIB and is limited to acute adult hospital presentations.","Amount or frequency, melaena or black-stool summary, dizziness or syncope, pain on defecation, anal inspection, family history, prior colonoscopy, coagulation testing, generic previous-record review, fixed follow-up intervals, PRN wording, and the combined history draft remain unsupported.","Diagnosis, bleeding source, severity, haemodynamic interpretation, risk-score calculation, investigation choice, treatment, transfusion, medicine changes, referral urgency, and disposition remain clinician responsibilities.","All prior supported legacy-item mappings were removed because canonical item-level applicability and workfl